 WHILE ENGAGED IN A HOVER THE ATP RATED PILOT, WHO HAD ONLY 9.0 HOURS OF 
ROTORCRAFT TIME OF WHICH 3.5 HOURS WERE SOLO, ALLOWED THE HELICOPTER 
TO DESCEND AND SLIP AFT. DURING THE ENSUING GROUND COLLISION THE 
HELICOPTER ROLLED OVER AND THE MAIN ROTOR BLADES IMPACTED THE 
GROUND. THE PILOT REPORTED THAT HE DIVERTED HIS ATTENTION TO A 
DEPARTING BUSINESS JET DURING WHICH TIME THE GROUND COLLISION 
OCCURRED. 
 THE PILOT IN COMMAND'S FAILURE TO MAINTAIN PROPER ALTITUDE DURING THE 
HOVER. FACTORS CONTRIBUTING TO THE ACCIDENT WERE THE PILOT IN 
COMMAND'S LACK OF TOTAL EXPERIENCE IN ROTORCRAFT AND HIS DIVERSION OF 
ATTENTION WHILE HOVERING. 
